  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Scholarships for Educational Opportunities</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In El Salvador, the economically active population averages only seven years of schooling, with approximately 7.2 years for boys and 6.9 years for girls. In addition, there is a lack of interest in market driven technical and vocational training which makes it difficult to find livelihood opportunities. Most of these people with no formal education cannot find employment. As a result, the low-income level and the rising poverty level becomes the main drivers of irregular migration as of 2020. To address the aforementioned challenges, IOM proposes a project to enhance access to formal educational opportunities for potential migrants, returnees and their families, in order to develop sustainable and competitive means of livelihoods and well-being, as part of efforts to mitigate irregular migration from El Salvador by increasing equitable access to formal educational opportunities for potential migrants and returnees to engender hope, prosperity, and positive self-worth in their lives.</narrative>
  </description>
